{
  "explanation": "The defendant is a first-time offender who has shown some level of accountability by partially repaying the embezzled funds. However, embezzling twenty-five thousand dollars constitutes a significant breach of trust and fiduciary duty. While the courtroom outburst suggesting a ten-year sentence represents an emotional and disproportionate reaction that has no bearing on this court's decision, a custodial sentence is still necessary to reflect the seriousness of the crime and serve as a deterrent. Taking into account the mitigating factors of a clean criminal record and active restitution, alongside the aggravating factor of the abuse of professional position, a brief period of incarceration is appropriate to balance punishment with rehabilitation and the continuation of restitution payments.",
  "verdict": 6
}
